This award allowed the PI?s group to contribute to the XENON1T project, a search for dark matter designed to detect possible interactions of these elusive particles with ordinary matter. The XENON1T detector was operated from 2016 to 2018. It features world-leading sensitivity to a variety of dark matter models. Its data are being used to search for signs of dark matter but there has been no discovery to date. The absence of a detection allowed to set very stringent limits on the nature of dark matter, rejecting several dark matter models and improving our knowledge on the topic. Thanks to its ultra-low background, XENON1T was used to measure the rarest radioactive decay ever directly detected, the two-neutrino double electron capture of 124Xe that features a half-life well in excess of the age of the Universe.



The award allowed also to establish a long term partnership with a local (minority-majority) high school - Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Preparatory College High School. One high school teacher had few week-long immersive experiences with the PI?s group and developed creative ways to integrate the PI?s research into her teaching. Beyond the teacher?s students, the program impacted directly also on planetarium stuff thanks to a dedicated workshop designed to provide a formal education session on dark matter (led by the PI?s group) and an example of how to implement it into high school curricula and planetaria (led by the teacher). Through the planetarium stuff the program impacted indirectly on a much broader public.

With support from this award the PI?s group contributed to the construction, commissioning and operation of the XENON1T detector. As far as the data analysis is concerned:



 the PI?s group led the development of a cyber-infrastructure, based on shared resources, that is used by the Collaboration to store the raw data produced by the experiment and process them to enable high level analyses. Due to its solid performance the pipeline backbones will be used also for the next phase of the program;
the PI?s group led the development of the Monte Carlo code used to simulate the response of the detector, estimate the expected background and inform various data analyses;
the PI?s group contributed to the main WIMP search (Weakly Interacting Massive Particle) and led few other analyses of dark matter models alternative to this, mostly electron mediated, as well as to neutrino-induced signals;






